03829nam a22005055i 9780773561076DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19861986xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735610767 a10.1515/97807735610762doi  a(DE-B1597)656872  a(OCoLC)1394873062  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPQ2625.A716bZ575 1986eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a843/.9121 aBevan, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAndré Malraux :bTowards the Expression of Transcendence /cDavid Bevan. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1986] 4c©1986  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOn “Le Miroir des limbes” -- tOn the Present Tense -- tOn Eroticism -- tOn Free Indirect Style -- tOn the Comic -- tOn Tibetan Symbolism -- tOn the Renunciation of the Novel -- tOn “Sierra de Teruel” -- tOn Feline Forms -- tOn Death and Dying -- tOn Oratory -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe two principal axes of inquiry are Malraux's ongoing quest for a dimension of transcendence within human life and, at lest as compelling, his search for the most appropriate and effective means by which to express a changing awareness of just what that dimension might be. Not surprisingly, in a world apparently doomed to languish in the spectral shadow of Death, there are certain constants: a yearning for some fraternity to combat man's essential solitude, a refusal to sink without effort into the vortex of the Absurd, a conviciton that life is to be lived fully and intensely. The human condition is what it is. The ways in which Malraux's characters, and of course Malraux himself, cope with this condition reveal a clear evolution, especially from the 1933 novel La condition humaine onwards. The reader follows Malraux from playful adolescence through the dichotomy of anguish and glorification in his middle years, towards the primarily interrogative utterances of the mature man. The often frivolous, sometimes sardonic, humour of youth gives way first to a painful recognition of the abyss, then to the discovery of a very tentative equilibrium in the philosophy of metamorphosis espoused by an older Malraux. André Malraux: Towards the Expression of Transcendence reveals the principal steps by which Malraux achieved that equilibrium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356107640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561076423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561076/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles